Jayco Stage 5 Results and GC

Simon Gerrans (AUS) - GEC: "I’m rapt to have the lead going into the last stage. It’s such a big deal for GreenEDGE to take the lead into the last stage in their first world tour outing so I’m thrilled and really rapt with the whole team’s performance, they have really supported me all week so I really can’t thank the guys enough."

Dave Sanders -Manager of UNISA

 “I’m very proud of these kids [for securing king of the mountain], I mean these are the best riders in the world, just got them to believe not to be afraid of them, to race them, you’ll either get there or you won’t but you can’t if you don’t have ago. I think we have secured the Mountain Jersey, probably Young Riders and possibly fifth maybe GC, so that’s pretty cool with young guys.”

Andrew Ryan, GreenEDGE management:

“We’ve worked so hard and now the team are working so hard and to get this result is just fantastic. Today was such a tough day, you know Simon was really on his own so it was amazing results that showed what he’s really capable of”.

How does it make you feel when you’re out on the road and you see GreenEdge caps everywhere? 

“Look it’s quite emotional like yesterday I was in the car with Matt White and people see the GreenEdge and start cheering, it’s just amazing. You do feel proud of what we have achieved, we are also proud for the Australian’s because they have an Australian team that they can really get behind”.

You’ve done a great job and the women have really set it off perfectly at the start of the season..

“The women have really set the bench mark. Its great theamount of coverage the women have been getting as well. Women’s sport doesn’t alwaysget the support it needs so that’s something we do try and do.”

Phil Anderson: 

"I think it was kind of expected [for an Australian team to lead] but it’s (bloody) fantastic! It’s very close, obviously it’s on the same time as Valverde from what I hear so it’s fantastic." 

How does it compare to your experiences and the Tour de France?

"I can’t believe it, it would have been great to be part of it as a racer but unfortunately that’s what happens, you know a couple of generations on now but it’s great to see Simon take the jersey and be a part of watching history go down here."

Edvald Boasson Hagen (NOR) - SKY: That was an incredible day out there and you managed to make yourself open to the break, how are you feeling now? “...really good from the team to keep on top of ... so they did a great job there and I managed to get up the climb first time so.... I felt really good and ...was really hard for me...so we managed to get over the top, so I’m so happy and the team did a great job today I thought.” Can you hold on tomorrow? “I’m not sure...... I hope I can keep the sprint jersey, maybe I can go a little bit higher up in the GC....”

Michael Rogers (AUS) - SKY: How difficult was it coming up to that 1 km? “The whole hill was pretty tough and there was strong head wind. The goal was to get everything out and scrape the bottom of barrel and I did that and I’m really happy.” Tough on the line? "I jumped with 400 meters to go and Valverde and got on my wheel and went when I blew. But I am really happy and it’s been a long time since I have been able to scrape the bottom of the barrel. It’s a win for myself and I am really happy.”

Nathan Haas (AUS) - GRM: What was going through your mind when you knew they were right behind you? "I thought my team mates are in that group so I thought moving out in front just gave them a sit on, and it would put some pressure on the legs of the other teams and I did that but unfortunately two of our riders got dropped and in the end it was only Jack Bauer. It was inevitable …I knew that I didn’t have the legs to make up the climb the second time." "[The race] is a good learning experience and it’s hard to get racing in this early period of the year so it’s nice to have a race under the belt and have the tour. I feel safe at the moment, injury free, we’ve still got tomorrow but I should be able to get through that. It’s been a nice experience to learn from the best riders in the world."

Alejandro Valverde (ESP) - MOV: “I’m super happy. I can’t believe it. My team has been genius. I’ve won thanks to them. It’s emotional moment for me. This win is for all the people who have supported me during my time off. This stage suited me. We put the team at the front and it’s a perfect comeback for me.”

Rohan Dennis (AUS - SA) - UNA You rode an incredible race today, you had no fear, you just took it to them, how do you feel now? “Yea the only way to do it is to put yourself in the race. I’m a little bit stuffed now but its all worth it in the end. I guess sometimes you need a little bit of form as well to have that confidence to actually go up the front but sometimes it’s just sort of a gut feeling, just sort of hope for the best”. There must be some of your idols in that... what goes through your mind when you doing that attack and realising the quality of riders behind you? “It’s always a bit of a worry because I know how good they actually are. I’m hoping they’re feeling or hurting as much as what I am. I just need to keep sort of positive when your at the front and you just think they’re hurting as much as you, really just stay as positive as possible”.

At the end of Jayco Stage five we spoke a few of the riders: Stuart O'Grady (AUS) - GEC: “It was seriously like an end of the Tour de France stage. Look at all the people, the stadium, the finish. I would never have dreamed a bike race to be as big in Australia, let alone Adelaide and the people have been absolutely fantastic. Coming up the hill today, it was like the tour.”

GreenEDGE Cycling is tantalisingly within touching distance of a dream World Tour debut after Simon Gerrans claimed the Ochre Race Leader’s jersey after a thrilling Jayco Stage 5 of the SANTOS Tour Down Under. It was almost the ultimate perfect day for Gerrans who made a dash for the stage win but went a fraction too early and couldn’t hold off the sprint of Alejandro Valverde (ESP) - MOV who recorded his first win since the 2009 Vuelta a Burgos. The margin was centimetres, but on a count back of places from throughout, Gerrans was awarded the Ochre jersey. Gerrans and Valverde will go in to tomorrow’s final stage on the same time, the first time this has happened since 2003. There are time bonuses on offer at the two Jayco Sprints with more on the finish line but it remains to be seen what strategies GreenEDGE and Movistar employ. Earlier the customary break was allowed the escape, pretty much as soon as the red flag dropped. Six riders went away : Stuart O'Grady (AUS) - GEC, Nathan Haas (AUS) - GRM, Takashi Miyazawa (JPN) - SAX, Kristof Goddaert (BEL) - ALM, Thomas de Gendt (BEL) - VCD and Andrew Fenn (GBR) - OPQ and claimed the two Jayco Sprints at Snapper Point (63.4km and 103.4km): Sprint 1: Kristof Goddaert (BEL) - ALM, Andrew Fenn (GBR) - OPQ and Stuart O'Grady (AUS) - GEC. Sprint 2: Thomas de Gendt (BEL) - VCD, Stuart O'Grady (AUS) - GEC, Andrew Fenn (GBR) - OPQ. Their lead grew to a maximum 8:10 before the peloton led mainly by BMC and Radioshack Nissan Trek began to reel them in. But the chase was entirely successful because they didn’t catch all the riders in break before the first ascent of Willunga Hill. Most of them succumbed but Nathan Haas (AUS) - GRM didn’t. He rode away on the early part of the climb and summated ahead of the fast moving peloton which by now was strung out down the hill. In fact Hass held on for most of the descent back into Willunga before a group of around 22 riders swamped him as they headed for the decisive second and final showdown on Willunga Hill. And as they began the final three kilometres of the stage, four riders made their move including Rohan Dennis (AUS - SA) - UNA, Javier Moreno (ESP) - MOV, Jan Bakelants (BEL) - RNT and Tiago Machado (POR) - RNT. Dennis and Moreno then seemed to be running away with it before Michael Rogers (AUS) - SKY made his move. The 2002 TDU champion looked set for a 10th anniversary repeat but could only watch in admiration as first Simon Gerrans (AUS) - GEC and then Alejandro Valverde (ESP) - MOV made their dash inside the final 500m. Gerrans surged to the front and with only the final left hand corner to go, looked to have Valverde’s measure. The Spaniard however had one more kick in him and it was too much for Gerrans as he bested him on the bend and edged over the line to snatch an emotional victory. It’s the second consecutive win by a Spaniard on Old Willunga Hill and the fourth in total. But Gerrans won’t be too disappointed with his day in the office. GreenEDGE have their much treasured Ochre Jersey and history tells us Gerrans will retain it tomorrow. If he does he’ll join O’Grady and Greipel as two time winners, but that dream has to wait, for now.

GreenEDGE sports director Matt White says his team will gamble Gerrans finishing ahead of Valverde on the finish line sprint tomorrow. He says he won't send Gerrans or GreenEDGE riders out chasing Jayco sprint bonuses.
